{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3b0ce4f9-14d9-440c-b711-2584bb109004","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is exactly what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — **reinstalls** the same versions already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't pull newer versions needed by the updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, verify the MAUI workload is present with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"addd0e7f-46f2-41a3-8abb-d23e879d9b7a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general .NET knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase for this.","outputTokens":234,"requestId":"77F6:E2933:7D77ED5:8BA0AE2:69EABD81"},"id":"989af2ab-5a1f-451e-b9a4-19ec3be33261","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:47:04.712Z","parentId":"09c3bb17-cd81-46e2-a799-dcbfdcdca44d"}
